Rating: 4
I've made this stew about half-dozen times, and it really can't be beat. The flavors are much richer than other stews. Browning the vegetables is a must, but I've adopted this variation: Instead of browning each veggie separately, I use a very large saute pan and brown in two batches: Carrots, celery and parsnips (the latter adds great flavor, and I highly recommend) in batch one, and the rest of the veggies in a second batch. I use a non-stick pan, which allows me to use about half of the butter called for in the recipe. I also use a combination of shallots and onions, and add some fresh peas during the last few minutes of cooking. Finally, I serve it over wide egg noodles. This stew has become a favorite among family and friends...and it's even better the next day!

Rating: 4
If you are looking for a gourmet beef stew, here it is! For 3-4 servings, I used 1.5 lbs beef, but same amount of liquid, mixing 1/4 cup sherry with wine. Also used more thyme and dried basil. I cut down veggies by 1/4 and sauteed together starting with longest cooking, adding more butter as I went along. Shitake mushrooms probably helped too.

